Parliament does not support the amendment that releases Tymoshenko
Today, the Parliament of Ukraine, in the course of amending the Code of Criminal Procedure, rejected an attempt to annul an article that condemned the leader of the opposition, Julia Timoshenko.
The amendment, which would result in the release of the former Prime Minister in prison, was rejected at the second reading of the draft law on commutation of sentences for economic offences.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for signing a gas deal with Russia, which was found to be unprofitable.
The sentence is not yet final; the court will consider the appeal of Tymoshenko in December.
Tymoshenko claims that the sentence is the political revenge of the regime; in the West, the process was also suspected of bias.
The proposal to repeal article 365 of the Code of Criminal Procedure, under which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was supported by 147 members of Parliament.
Ratification would require 226 votes.
