Eating Obesity Children: No Breakfast and Sausage for Dinner
More than a third of children between the ages of 9 and 13 weigh more than the norm; while 9 per cent of pupils are overweight, 5 per cent are obese.
According to a recent study, children who suffer from obesity usually come from unhealthy families.
Once again, we see the importance of the environment and the behaviours associated with humans for their or their healthy development.
For example, sausage is almost twice as common on the table of children with obesity as it is in families with children with normal weight.
More than 19 per cent of children suffering from obesity ate fries for dinner on the eve of an educational event called Obesity is not an accident.
In addition, the families of obese children do not engage in sport, but most of the families of modern school children say that only 15 per cent of the children say that their parents take time to sport at least once a week.
The study was conducted among 900 children.
The study was carried out at the end of the last school year, with nearly 900 pupils in primary school throughout Bohemian.
The Obesity event was not an incident for the second year in a row, with the support of the insurance company Všeobecná zdravotní pojišovna and Unilever.
To date, more than 12,000 pupils in grades 4 to 8 have joined the project.
Good diet and sufficient sporting activity are the main determinants of the rapidly growing number of children who suffer from either overweight or obesity.
"For example, only half of the interviewees said that they eat five times a day, on the basis of a lunch lunch lunch lunch luncheon, which is one of the basic conditions for proper diet," says one of the findings of the study.
No lunch and no sausage at night.
Experts warn that even relative details, such as the constant time of family lunch, are important for healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, only 23 per cent of school families have breakfast together.
Most families have separate breakfasts.
The worst discovery is that in every 10 families, people don't even have breakfast.
Still, breakfast is the basis of the right day's diet.
The study found that fried food is more common in families with obese children.
Almost everyone, regardless of weight, drinks sweet, cool drinks every day (70%).
Although more than 40 per cent of children are regularly engaged in sports, this figure is more than halved, to 15 per cent, when it comes to their parents.
Make a menu of your own.
In another part of the study, selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) were asked to draw up their own menus on the basis of the products offered and on the basis of their tastes and preferences.
"The food preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 are far from the ideal of a healthy diet."
Their favorite food includes a large number of flour, meat, and sweet dishes.
“A particular concern is the high popularity of sweet cooling drinks,” says the final part of the study.
As the main meal, the pasta beat the bird with a small margin.
However, children have shown little interest in beans, fish, and vegetable dishes.
The Strength for a Healthy Lifestyle
The study also showed that children are prepared to change their eating habits on the condition that they are provided with relevant information.
“Many members of the control group of studies have shown a significant shift in preferences towards healthy food when they complete the questionnaire after completion of the Obesity lecture is not an accident,” states the project's outcome.
This was particularly evident, for example, in the case of sweet, cool drinks - more children started to prefer them to just water.
In addition, children more frequently observed bird and fish, limiting the number of sweet dishes and baking.
