V Need for Speed: The escape takes place in America.
Overview
What was supposed to be a careless walk turned into a routine morning trip to work because of a series of totally inappropriate and careless mistakes.
Ambiguities had been met to a certain degree, but that was not important, since no one clearly wanted to do any extra work.
Before the new version with the subtitle "Running" went out, there was a lot of hope.
It was expected to move the previous series of Need For Speed in a new direction; the showcases showed that the game would take a proper place in the genre of the race.
We were curious to see the parts of the game where the main character got out of the car and ran.
As is often the case with NFS, in the end, much is different from what we expected.
The game is a pretty good arcade race, but the general impression is corrupted by a number of unnecessary errors that have been present in this series of games for a number of years.
So, in fact, it's not a mistake, it's an inexplicable laziness of the developers.
The adventure starts very well.
You're becoming part of a history whose main hero, Jack, solves some personal problems by taking part in an illegal race through America.
You get in a car on the west coast in San Francisco, and it's your job to get to New York first.
This idea has a number of interesting features.
The route consists of 10 steps divided by more than fifty races.
This means that each race takes its own route, and the individual stages take place in a diverse and interesting environment.
So it doesn't feel like the game is the same all the time.
Although the charts are at the same level as in the previous parts of the series, it is a pleasure to look at some of the tracks.
Still, the game does not cause strong emotions.
Though it is a pleasure to drive through the desert, in the autumn suburbs, or high in the snowy mountains.
In addition, the race occasionally revives an unusual detail.
In the desert, for example, you find yourself in a sandstorm that significantly reduces the visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you have to be careful not to get under a hole.
The individual races are fairly well organized.
There are only a few varieties, but that's enough.
For a while you're trying to outrun a few rivals (in fact, a normal race); then you're trying to improve the time (standard race with a second meter); or you're competing with one adversary.
Among other things, you occasionally run into a police force that makes your task even more difficult.
The components outside the car are new.
It's just an interactive animation, where most of the time Jack's running away from someone, and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's not a big deal.
Though it is surprising that these fragments are much smaller than you might expect (three to be accurate).
In fact, it turns out that it's good for the game, because it's not boring; given all the above, it's one of the things that makes the game more fun.
The race model follows the tracks of the previous models.
This means that it is no longer something special, but it can't be considered a disadvantage.
If you're looking for a real life imitation, you're gonna have to look elsewhere.
Still, this model of driving is very good for dynamic races, although there are better options on the market.
So far, so good.
But after a while, problems start.
Unlike the driving model, the crash model is not that good.
You don't expect this kind of game to be a complex transformation or a collision, but if you don't know how your machine will act, something's wrong.
Normally, bypassing or bypassing cars in a dense flow, you sometimes touch the other car a little bit, but sometimes, in a virtually similar situation, your car starts to spin wildly.
Or it's cracked.
It's not that important because of the restart system, but it's enough to ruin the fun.
Restarts are designed so that if you break up or go far off the track, the game returns you to the point where it crashed.
However, only five re-starts are available for each race.
If you use them all, you'll have to start the race from the start.
It's good if something doesn't work out, but you can't totally rely on it.
Sometimes restarting is not enough, and you have to memorize a separate race.
An important shortcoming of the game is the fact that the same things often happen in the same place.
For example, some twists have to go in a certain way, or you just don't fit in.
In other cases, you meet a civilian car in a particular location in the same configuration, whether you come first, fifth, five seconds earlier, or a minute later.
This is particularly frustrating in situations where you see your opponent traveling easily between two cars moving in the opposite direction, whereas when you are there, the machines are already positioned in such a way that you need to either cross them or slow down.
It doesn't matter when you're next to them; it's like it's always happening right in front of you.
There are other advantages to rivals.
During the game, you find a number of places where, no matter what time, the same rival overtakes you in the same place.
It's particularly evident at the end of the game, on the long bridge, where you drive in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your opponent must stand before you no matter what.
The thing is, when he's coming in front of you, he's making you look worse, which leads to one or more accidents in this area.
You can understand an attempt to make the game more interesting and adrenaline-full, but it's so obvious that it's starting to get irritated fast.
It's a pity, because despite the simple model of driving, the game is fascinating, and sometimes so full of events, that you don't have time to pay attention to what's happening around you.
It doesn't matter what makes you miss -- a concept with fifty unique tracks, a race sequence or something.
The idea of changing cars during the race is unusual.
You need to track the gas stations along the way, because that's what your car can switch on, despite the fact that in most cases the one you already have is enough.
Cars are divided into three categories.
Sports machines are good for cities; powerful American cars are good for direct stretches of the highway; and exotic super-sports for technical driving, for example, on curved mountain tracks.
The main mode of story mode is closely linked to the challenge mode; it is a race on individual sites that you will learn as the game progresses.
Here you win for your personal business, both medals and glasses common to challenges and story.
Many of the possibilities are available for obtaining a higher level of driving, from the machine to the profile data.
In addition, the profile is linked to the online function Autolog, which, among other things, compares the results you have achieved with those of other players, and provides public relations.
Here's another flaw that's hard to understand; it's an example from the last race in sequence.
You and your car get into the subway tunnel (let's think so) where you run down the tracks in the dark (let's think so).
Your speedometer shows the numbers from 150 to 200 km/h (let's say so) when a subway train suddenly hits you in the back, turning your car into a pile of scrap metal.
For a few days, our editors have been discussing whether at the time of the game, no one really thought for a second, or whether the creators really think we're such idiots.
The technical component of the game is not a big deal; but the overall impression from the video series is mostly pleasant, sometimes even amazing.
While it is a pity that at some critical moments the quality of the record is sometimes very high, the quality of the record is declining.
This is particularly the case with a large number of participants, where a good record would not be very helpful to you, either.
Sound is fine; soundtrack is on the amateur.
To please as wide a youth audience as possible, the soundtrack's "compositions from different styles"; but it's not likely that a lot of people will buy the game because of its music.
The general impression of Need for Speed: The escape is rather messy.
If the game were to avoid obviously unnecessary mistakes, we could honestly say that the run is the best part of the NFS in the last few years.
In any case, the game leaves a sense of incompleteness.
Of course, it's a good fun, but be prepared to see your inadequacies blind you as a spotlight at the airport.
