Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies could work in the former Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea, and Autotourist.
As travel to the West was severely restricted, the travel agencies of the time were mostly selling tours to the socialist bloc.
Thus, during the holidays, Czech tourists travelled to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea, Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime returned to the West, which led to significant restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
A major paradox of the socialist period was that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed to travel individually to socialist countries.
If a Czechoslovakia citizen wanted to go on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation was needed from that country; otherwise, an individual journey was not possible.
At the time, travel agencies offered to travel to the West, but either to stand in line all night, with a sleeping bag, or to have "good friends" in the agency.
And that wasn't all.
Currency permission was needed to travel to the West, and it was not given to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; it was not possible to obtain money (Western currency) for travel to the West without a currency permit.
Most of the time the Czechs spent their vacations at home, which led to large numbers of cottages and summer homes, a habit that still exists today.
After 1989, tourism in the Czech Republic thus experienced a real revolution.
While until 1989 leave to the GDR or Bulgaria was the culmination of our travels, last year the Czechs held 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world.
The great paradox, which we no longer know, is that before 1989 we were not able to freely visit Croatia, which is now the most popular, as it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the very beginning of 1990 the need to obtain a visa to neighbouring countries in Western Europe was abolished, and this led to a huge wave of short trips, mostly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakia had no way of enjoying their trips to the West, and everyone wanted to go there for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents because their income at the time was insufficient for a hotel or boarding home.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the drive to bring in their own food (conserves, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech crown, and after decades, our tourists are finally free to buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income have increased, which has led to another important situation around 1997.
Since 1997, the increased demand has enabled travel agencies to prepare regular flights by charter airlines, and in comparison with the past, air travel has become incredibly cheap because of the ability to order bulk discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, the Czechs did not need a visa to visit almost all the developed world, except the US, which made our travels even easier.
The next major event in the history of post-revolution travels occurred in 2000, and the high demand has led to the historic first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have been transporting Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and this winter flight from the Czech Republic will take 12 exotic routes.
Today, about 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US cancelled the need for a visa for Czech tourists, and our country has thus forever joined the world's most developed countries.
For the first time in history in 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their vacations abroad (50.3 per cent); and for the first time in history, they spent more than 15,000 kroner per person during the foreign vacation, including their spending at their destination.
