Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which is awarding the Nobel Prize for Literature.
The book that he's writing now is unusual, he describes it, quite precisely, as "work on anti-history."
There are few known names, important treaties or famous battles; there are hardly any ambassadors, sloppy journalists, or discussions of tactics and combat technology.
It's not so much a book about what happened, - he explains - it's a book about what it was like.
The book "Beauty and Pilgrimage" combined the experience of 20 more or less unattractive men and women, on both sides of the front line, from schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, ambulance drivers and employees.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Someone's gonna go into captivity, lose a hand or a leg, go crazy or die.
Their lives are flickering here like church candles: new ones are added to a lot of others, and some are fading at the time.
Mr. Englund's book is a departure from the standard of historical books.
This is also an amendment to the idea that the First World War was just a gravel war on the West Front.
Beauty and Pilgrimage provides a skillful panorama of other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, and East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are hit by bee hives; one of them meets Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; the unsolved problem is the tsetse fly.
