The walls have eyes: how researchers study you on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremists in Europe, Anders Bering Bravik was a regular guy who spoke his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Bravik, who had confessed to the massacre in Norway in July, which had claimed the lives of 77 people, appeared at his first public trial.
Although Bravik could act alone, he was far from being single online: he spent a lot of time preparing to attack his computer, in contact with millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups in social media.
After the summer tragedy, the researchers wanted to learn more about these people.
But how do we find them?
Easy, you just have to go to Facebook.
"We realized that it was not hard to get close to them," says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report on the European cyber populism of the British DEMOS Research Center.
Facebook's personal data is so big, says Bartlett, that researchers could easily use the website's advert to single out the required population group with scientific certainty - that marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett's team found half a million right-wing fans all over Europe and then tipped them off with ads, but instead of displaying a new group or a diet product, the ads offered the user a poll that included questions about the level of their education, the attitude to violence, and the optimism about their own future.
With Facebook's help, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview more than 10,000 members of 14 extreme right-wing parties in 11 European countries, not even leaving the office.
"This is a brand-new way to do research," says Bartlett.
Some of the results are not as amazing: online right-handers are most often male youths who are dissatisfied with immigration.
But suddenly, "those who combine their online activity with offline activity are more intelligent, more democratic and less aggressive than those who are just hiding behind the monitor."
The work of DEMOS is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new popular tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers, and polytologists use the site to study everything in the world, from health to social trends in the Laikas, wall posts, and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users, adding an average of three entries a day, Facebook's "super-actual information" has caused a research boom, increasing the number of scientific articles with the name of the site in the headline by 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, Facebook’s beauty is that it offers an opportunity to study people who cannot be reached on the street with a notebook.
"In the past, if you wanted to interview people from the British National Party, it would be very difficult to identify them."
"You'd have to join the party, and they'd never accept you," Bartlett says.
"Facebook excludes all of this - you address them directly."
Others say that this site could be used to identify and investigate social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues showed that students who had discussed their drunken Facebook performances were at a much higher risk of alcoholism than students who had been quiet about it.
Moreno suggests that student peers, such as their hostel instructors, can monitor the site and interfere to help a student who too often updates his drinking status.
"You can't solve the problem without finding it," said Washington Post Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Moreno and Director of the Centre for Children's Health, Behaviour and Development at the Seattle Children's Research Institute.
"We've found a way to identify children from a risk group that we wouldn't have found otherwise."
Facebook also regularly extracts various kinds of data about its users.
The website's data processing team processed the status statistics and Valentine's Day, the mid-term turnout in 2010 as well as the National Index of Happiness (mainly using information available to them - cyber-free champions long insisted that the site should make its vast collection of data publicly available for research).
But Facebook users know that the site watches them, whether they like it or not, in exchange for playing Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away, the site can process your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a study they don't even know about?
While researchers have strict standards for off-line research, online data is publicly available.
"I don't think a lot of users have at least thought that a researcher can watch their profile," says Neil Selvin, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, about a study that he did in 2006 using a public Facebook student page.
"As far as they imagined, it was between them and their friends."
That raises the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that the subject of the study is very honest.
On Facebook, it is not possible to find out how much information on the profile and on the user's page is correct.
"What you say on Facebook, and what you do outside Facebook, are two completely different things," says Selvin.
That is why, despite years of work in the field of technology, Selvin thinks that the notebook and the pen are still the best research tools that can be used.
"Nothing can replace a way out of the real world and with real people," he says.
"Social research is supposed to be about social research, and most social research is still offline."
