Seven lessons from Steve Jobs' lost interview, which is shown at the theater this week.
After Steve Jobs died on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, describing a technical genius as the Great Inventor of Modernity.
But what Apple fans might consider to be the biggest discovery in the recent re-detected interview, which was recalled in the run-up to the major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood in business processes and in production technologies.
He was, of course, a designer, a dreamer and considered himself a hippie, but he was also a thorough organizer and modernizer of the production process, who believed that many business leaders had suffered from "the pain of thinking that a really great idea is 90 percent of the job ... [but] the great idea of a great product separates a huge amount of skill."
Let's go back to 1995, Bob Kringley created a TV series of Nerd Triumph on the arrival of a personal computer, and he spent over an hour with Jobs for a uniquely long conversation.
By that time, it had been about 10 years since Jobs had been kicked out of Apple, and he had been working at his new computer company, NeXT, in anticipation of the massive development of the Internet.
While a small part of Kringley's interview was used in the Nerds, he says that the original interviews went missing during the transport.
It was only after Jobs' death that a full VHS copy was found in the director's garage.
This film, a bit edited, became the basis for the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: Lost interview, which is released at Landmark Theaters this Wednesday and Thursday.
For a man who is known for his hating detailed interviews, Jobs seems unfamiliar here to express his technological philosophy and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
At four different moments in the interview, there's a big gap between questions and answers -- 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, where Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts to be more accurate.
There are also moments where Jobs's perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems to be irritated by Kringley's questions, which make him move more quickly to questions or events of greater importance.
In the pre-Picsar era, iPods and iPhones of the Lost interview, there is something ominous prophetic when Jobs evaluates what he sees different companies do right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of information technology.
It's one thing to read about postmortem evaluations of Jobs' work, but there's something sensitive and inspiring about Jobs that we see here, a troubled dreamer on the verge of grandeur.
He has a vision of what things could and should be.
Shortly after he said it all here, he went and did it.
A brief account of the seven significant findings of the Lost Interview:
About how he learned to run a business:
"For all the time in the business, I've always asked, "Why are you doing this?" And the answers that you always get are, "Oh, that's just how it's done."
No one knows why they do what they do, no one thinks very deeply in business.
That's what I learned.
Jobs continues to detail his attempts to streamline the accounts in Apple.
A disillusioned way of recording the costs, which often began with “standard costs” that were taken from the ceiling and then followed up with a “unique”, he created an automated structure that ensured that they would be able to track the business outlays up to the details.
About the pope joke:
Jobs details the "blue box" he made with Steve Wozniak, a device that allowed people to hack the phone company effectively and call for free long distances.
There's been a lot of writing about the device before, but Jobs' euphoria here, describing the blue box as an act of power is contagious.
He talks about how he and Wozniak were testing the box using a computer phone, ordering a conversation, and then connecting from one AT&T network to the next, until they linked as many stations as possible.
"We've covered the globe half a dozen times, and you've been yelling at the machine phone, and it's been coming in a minute later on to the next phone," says Jobs with a smile.
"We were young, and all we learned was that we could build something that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure all over the world."
We both knew a little bit, but we could build a little thing that could control a big thing - it was an incredible lesson, and I don't think that without it, Apple could ever show up.
Jobs continues to describe in detail a famous incident that he and Wozniak almost managed by calling the Vatican via a blue box at midnight and by calling the Pope, trying hard to copy Henry Kissinger.
When the different members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to talk to the American diplomat, the two laughter exploded just before the Pope himself was raised to answer the phone.
About the love of technology (and the cold name Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, he was looking for spare parts to collect the frequencies, and he found Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone call, Jobs received a summer job in Hewlett Packard.
"It had a strong impact on me, "it was the only company I had ever seen at that age, "and it shaped my view of what a company is and how well they treat their employees."
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw the "best desktop computer".
It was the size of a suitcase, it had a small monitor with an electronic ray tube, and I fell in love with it.
I used to go to HP when I was a teenager and go around that car and write programs for it.
On improvised innovation:
In a number of places, Jobs talks about the invention of new products for the summer.
At the dawn of his career, when he went to sell a handful of installments, a buyer asked him to collect a complete computer.
