Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we were able to collect for $15, which was incredibly reliable.
About the big companies that are losing power:
Long before he led Apple's renaissance, Jobs foresaw exactly how many industry leaders would misunderstand the situation and lose control of their market share.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make the best copier or printer, and what?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the company's not getting any more successful.
Sale and marketing make it more successful, so [these types of people] who end up running companies, and the people who make the product are being pushed off the decision-making site.
The genius of the product that led to this monopolistic position is replaced by people who have no idea of the difference between good and bad products - the required skill.
