Climate issues slowed the economy
During the first year of Mario López's reign in Sinaloa, unemployment and the illegal labour market rose, foreign financing declined, and the economy was weakened.
2011 is the year that will enter the economic history of Sinaloa as linked to the first year of the Government of Mario López Valdez, also called the Year of Change, which has raised high hopes for economic development, but, given the adverse climate conditions of the beginning of the year, there has been no growth, but there has been a decline in basic economic development.
The low temperatures of February not only lost millions in the agricultural sector, but they limited the growth potential of the public economy, leading to a total decline of 3.6 per cent in economic activity in the first half of the year, mainly due to the historic drop of 31.16 per cent in agriculture, which affected the performance of other sectors of the economy.
According to the report on the areas affected by the frost, provided by the Council for Sustainable Rural Development of Mexico, 835,582 hectares have been affected, of which 78.03 per cent have been entirely affected, while the remaining 21,07 per cent have been partially affected, with the main damaged crops being vegetables, maize and mute.
The decline in economic activity led, until November, to a steady rise in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, in the first three quarters, to an accelerated increase in the rate of unemployment, from January to March 55,053 Sinaloa had been unemployed, with a share of 4.53 per cent of the economically active population, in the second quarter to 5.28 per cent, and from July to September it had continued to grow to 6.19 per cent, a proportion of more than 74,000 Sinloa unemployed people, an increase of 18.969 in comparison with the first half.
Reduced liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa over the course of the year has been addressed by many factors, for economist Gerardo López Cervantes, the Director of the Department of Economics and Social Sciences of the Autonomous University (UAS), the rise in unemployment can be explained indirectly by actions taken in public policy.
“What we see now is an increase in unemployment, which is linked to a number of factors, including the loss of market liquidity to limit the resources imposed by the law adopted by Congress to combat money-laundering, since it is not easy for people who illegally own dollars to work with them, invest and use them in something,” he said.
Stopped immigration
López Cervantes said that there is also a demographic factor in the rise in unemployment.
"The number of people who leave the state in search of work abroad has been limited in the US, primarily because of the difficulty of entry, and in the second, because once they have entered, they are already facing very many difficulties in finding work, so that a group of people stay and demand jobs here in the state, as a result of which the unemployment rate is rising," he said.
Violation of formal requirements
The analysis of the Sinaloa labour market is getting worse if you consider the high incidence of labour-related disorders, according to INEGI, that 60,38 per cent of the active population of the state works without being mentioned as employees in any social protection institution.
In addition to unemployment and irregularity, another reminder of the state ' s work is presented by low wages; in the State, the lowest wages in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Ministry of Labour and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was up to September 5,352 pesos, well below the national average of 7,375 pesos.
FDI reduction
In addition to the decline in economic activity and the high rate of unemployment, the largest outflow of foreign direct investment in the past 10 years, according to the Ministry of Finance, was $630,697 from January to July. This represents a decline of 87.74 per cent, compared to $5,143,312 over the same period last year.
For its part, the State Government's Ministry of Economic Development recorded only 17,280,000 peso-investment during the year, which was largely the product of service companies.
Duty
Against the background of the economic downturn, the state government in July requested the approval of a 3-billion-peso loan to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 municipalities to revive the economy, at the local level, only 2,600 million pesos had been approved, and until November there had been no debt advantage in any sector of the state economy.
Responses
For business representatives, Mario López Valdez's first year of government shows a lack of government capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Manufacturing, said that in 2011 there was a lack of agreement on the wishes of different sectors, including the state government itself.
“The efficiency of the Sinaloa economy has been really low this year, has to work hard to get back the positions lost this year, we have to redouble our efforts in 2012, we have failed to agree on the efforts of all and, above all, the good and synchronized work of the new government team, we hope that next year will be much better,” he said.
The slowing down of the economy
López Loredo said that events like the early freezes this year stopped the state economy and its efficiency and growth were limited.
“The low levels of the economy are the result of a number of events, including the frost, and one of the main effects was the slow economy, which is not getting fast enough to create an economic dynamic that allows for an acceptable level of processes, goods and services and, therefore, at the end of the year, we close it below our expectations,” he said.
Revision of the heading
Theodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said that the state needed to continue its most dynamic production activity.
“In general, we have found that we have been working on this, we believe that there is a need to develop a long-term programme that will rethink the direction and economic course of the state, and to mobilize all the material and human resources that Sinaloa has,” he said.
Work to be undertaken
President Coparmex stressed the importance of determining the future direction in order to better guide the Government's efforts.
“In general, I would say that the Government is trying to be successful in various fields, and there is little progress in terms of economic development, but it is important to develop a long-term programme,” he said.
He noted that the current administration had shown progress in its own way of public policy.
"There are facts that allow us to say that the government is starting to get involved in the work, and that I can say that some work has been done, and I think the government is aware that much more needs to be done," he said.
