The court will approve the “transition to digital television” in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analogues to digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has experienced in recent years.
The Supreme Court (JC) rejected the constitutional motions made by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the Presidential Decree, which moved the so-called “transition to digital television” from 2021 to 2015, as eight votes had not been obtained to annul it.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Mesa, considered that President Felipe Calderon had not exceeded his authority by issuing a decree detailing the steps taken to move to digital ground television.
As a result, the constitutional claims made by the Senate had been rejected because of the absence of a qualified majority of the eight votes required for the court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remained in force.
The draft statement, prepared by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed that the decree be declared unconstitutional, because the regulation of the radio and television programme was a right established by law for the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the legislative reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Marguerite Luna and Sánchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
On this point, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to disprove the decree and support the complaints, and Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions referred to in the decree regarding the move to digital broadcasting.
It was also decided at the Ministerial Meeting to reject the request of the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the discussion of the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he did not agree with the argument of the project in the sense that the federal executive cannot determine the general rules for the measures to be prepared by the public administration.
“I also do not believe that this would have affected the autonomy of the regulator” and recalled that planning public policy in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, is relevant to the federal executive, which has a constitutional mandate, the administration of the State.
Replacing analogues to digital signals, one of the most important changes that have taken place in recent years, has led to better use of the radio-electric spectrum, better quality of the signal, and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would mean postponing the benefits of transforming into a digital form, which includes meeting public needs, which have more than a technical dimension, “because it covers economic, social, political and national security issues”.
These questions, he said, “requests the work of a whole system of public economic governance, including a group of authorities, which the Constitution unites into the State executive branch”.
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the transition to digital broadcasting, and had done so with the help of the executive, despite the existence of highly specialized technical institutions.
From this it cannot be concluded that the Government, by adopting the decree under discussion, which in any event affects the competence of the Congress, has said that the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly shall be enforced in the administrative sphere.
In Michoacana, the possibility of counting "vote-by-vote" is being analysed.
According to the data submitted to the PRRA, the difference between the first and second seats in the Governor ' s elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes of 879 of the total of 6.074 protocols.
The possibility of counting a “vote-for-vote” is real with regard to the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where, according to the Provisional Results Programme (PPP), the difference between the first and second seats in the Governor's elections is only 27 per cent, even without counting 879 of the total of 6.074 protocols.
In the light of this, the President of the General Council of the Michokan Electoral Institute (IMI), Maria de Los Angeles Lianderal Saragos, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the Electoral Corps had adopted a set of principles to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
It should be recalled that Michoacán did not adopt the Constitution or the State Electoral Code or the Electoral Law Act, as the State Congress approved the reforms just before the legal deadline for their entry into force in the electoral process, and the Governor, Leonel Godoy Rangel, did not include its publication in the time frame set out in the Act in the State Official Gazette, stating that he had some objections.
On the same day, 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice (JJJJ) ruled on a constitutional claim made by the local legislature and called the state's representative's vote on constitutional reform “unvalid and illegal” because it had no right to “permit or support it”.
In an interview on the possibility of a “vote-for-vote” Maria de los Angeles Landerall claimed that, with the adoption of suitable principles by the General Council of IWM, it would be possible to present a partial or complete count of the votes by the local electoral body.
For example, a partial recalculation of one or more ballot boxes can be made on the condition that: the results of the records are not consistent; there is no record of the voting and the counting of the documents in the urn or it is not in the hands of the chairman; or when there are obvious errors or corrections in the record.
In addition, a total recalculation of the votes in all the urns in the elections may take place when there is a sign that the difference between the alleged winner of the elections in question and the second-place candidate is less than or equal to one per cent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a request from the party and/or coalition representative who put out the second of the candidates in question.
A total recount will also be made if, at the end of the normal count, it is determined that the difference between the winner and the second-place candidate is less than or equal to 1 per cent, provided that there is a request from the political party, whose candidate is second-placed, in the event that the ballot boxes, which have been taken into account in the partial recalculation, are excluded.
It is worth noting that this is the case in Morellia, where, according to the PDRP, the difference between first and second place is only 0.16 per cent, even if the number of votes is 129 out of a total of 923 protocols.
