A new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The appointed Prime Minister, Mario Monty, will meet tomorrow with the Italian President to present a new government that will face the crisis that put this country on the verge of an economic catastrophe.
The appointed Italian Prime Minister, Mario Monty, will meet with the Italian president on Wednesday to present a new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the edge of an economic catastrophe and has damaged the entire eurozone.
A statement from the Presidential Palace stated that Monty, appointed on Sunday, would meet with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he could form a government.
He is expected to present a mainly technocratial cabinet, although it is not clear when the new executive body will take up its positions.
Monty said that he would present to the President the results of his talks with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to reaffirm my full confidence in the country's ability to get out of this difficult period," said the former European Commissioner to reporters.
Monty did not explicitly say that he was able to form a government, but the tone of his comments showed that the obstacles had been overcome.
"The article is now well-designed," he said.
Monty completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than usual, as Italy was struggling with the political and financial crisis, which brought their debt to a critical level.
The administration, under the leadership of the former European Commissioner Monty, must approve the austerity package required by European leaders to restore confidence in Italy.
On the basis of the pressure on Monty to rush it, the unstable markets have set up a 10-year profit from the BTP bonds of Italy over 7 per cent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marchegalia, the leader of the Italian Federation of Employers, told the reporters after the meeting with Monty, "We said we would actively support this government."
We believe that this government is Italy's last chance to get out of this critical situation.
Monty's chances of success were largely based on the support of the Sylvio Berlusconi LDP party, who was forced to resign on Saturday because of the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monty's efforts should lead to a good outcome," said Angelino Alphano, the secretary of the centralist-right party.
The support of the LDP, the largest party in Italy, is important, because so far many of its members have resisted the government majority of technocrats that form Monty.
Parliamentary support
The new Monty government must have strong parliamentary support for reform, which is likely to be unpopular reforms of austerity.
Any blocking or halting of these attempts can lead to a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian Association of Foreign Banks has increased pressure, warning that Monty's failure can be a disaster.
Monty began his consultations with political parties, unions and business groups, as well as with youth and women's organizations, on Monday.
He'll finish a series of his meetings on Tuesday night.
Monty was appointed on Sunday, Napolitano, who resolved a very fast transition in response to the crisis.
After a short break at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would be retiring, the cost of Italy’s debt had now reached a critical level, given the uncertainty as to whether the new Prime Minister would be successful.
Salvaging Italy with a public debt of Euro1.8 billion would be too much for modern euro-zone financiers.
Monty said that his government would be in place until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite the widespread predictions that politicians would only give him time to reform before he could appoint a new election.
Monty said he'd like to include politicians in his office, but the major parties insist that it should be composed of technical experts only, a sign of their dissatisfaction with the fact that the financial situation is affecting the process.
Political sources reported that the mutual distrust and dissent of the parties made it more difficult to try to include political figures.
