Fujimori was hospitalized again for a medical examination.
Ex-president Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized on Tuesday at the public hospital, and his family doctor told him to test for the loss of muscle in his legs.
Fujimori, aged 72, who was sentenced to 25 years in prison for human rights violations committed during his reign (1990-2000), suffers from a number of diseases, including language cancer, which has led to his operation four times and being monitored.
Congressman Alejandro Aginaga, who is his private doctor, told TV channel N that Fujimori would be examined in three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the cause of pain and loss of power in his lower limbs.
Aginaga said that in his view Fujimori should be a candidate for the benefit of pardon for humanitarian reasons; however, he said that he did not want it because he knew he was innocent.
He had undergone four tests on language cancer, lost 18 kilograms of weight, to which other diseases, such as a strong erosion gastrit, pancreas cysts, kidney rocks, high blood pressure, and blood flow problems in his legs, were listed by the doctor.
Fujimori has been in prison since September 2007, at the National Police Department of Special Operations.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the murder of 25 people by the army's extermination force, which operated secretly during the first years of his reign.
Mujika is going to Mexico to fortify political ties
An official delegation led by the President of Uruguay, José Mujica, and composed of several ministers and businessmen, will come to Mexico this Tuesday to expand trade between the two countries and to start negotiations on the political problems of the region.
Mujika will meet next Wednesday with her Mexican colleague, Felipe Calderon, the most important point in the vast plan of meetings with the political, commercial and community of Uruguayans living in Mexico, according to a timetable published by the Uruguayan leadership.
The meeting of the two presidents in Guadalajara will be “favourable for the exchange of information on political relations between the two nations,” as the South American leadership has published on its website.
According to the local media, Mujica is seeking support for the Calderon for Uruguay in an incident with France when French President Nicolas Sarkozy listed the South American country as a tax haven at a G20 meeting in the French city of Canne.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remained tax havens a statement that had provoked a protest by Uruguay and a withdrawal for consultations by his Ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group of the most developed and developing countries, and in fact has had an agreement with the South American country since January this year to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
In recent years, the Government of Uruguay has tried to speed up the conclusion of tax-exchange agreements in order to leave the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development's grey list, drawn up from countries that do not enjoy international standards of tax cooperation.
With regard to the trade plan, Mexico and Uruguay had had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004, which had increased trade between the two countries.
