"This information reinforces the hypothesis of a normal summer manoeuvre at the moment of impact," he said.
At a press conference, the owner of SCT, Perez Hacome, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the air rules, the flight was carried out according to the rules of visual flight, which means that the crew must be visible during the flight and landing.
Weather conditions:
The AICM reports identified suitable conditions for take-off when the aircraft was heading to the border between Mexico City and the State of Mexico, where the layers of clouds were observed at low altitudes.
Selected routes:
It is possible that because of the cloud conditions, the team was looking for a smaller and more visible area in the Cuernavac Valley.
Place of impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last record of the aircraft's radar are the same, and it is likely that there was no loss of control or a change of direction prior to the impact.
Scatter of fragments in a small area:
The information available to date indicates that the impact occurred on the front and side lines.
The dispersion of the wreckage shows that the helicopter was impacted by structural integrity.
There were no obvious signs of fire or explosion:
In the area of the disaster, there is undiscovered evidence in the wreckage of the ship, some kind of explosion or fire.
Recent studies have shown that there may have been multiple contacts with the land.
During their work on the ground, fragments of an aircraft were found at a height of 9,200 feet above sea level, and the ground has a gradient of between 7 and 30 degrees.
The images show the sequence in which it collapsed along the way.
The information contains facts that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have had several collisions with the ground.
After a thorough study in more territory than the delimited zone near the site of the crash, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found, which reinforces the assumption that the impact occurred in a context of structural integrity.
MSS announces the obesity gene search program
Social protection leads research on the obesity gene in children and young people; it is supported by IPN experts
The Mexican Institute for Social Protection (MSSI) has announced that it is conducting a study to detect the obesity gene in children and young people, which is known as the protocol “Genetics of Obesity in Childhood and Adolescence”, which will provide an estimate of signs of overweight.
In his statement, the head of the Biochemistry Unit of the Specialized Hospital of the National Health Centre of the 21st Century, Miguel Cruz Lopez, explained that a multidisciplinary team of physicians, nurses, dietologists and social workers had been assembled.
The team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Health of the Nation (NIPH) and the Centre for Scientific Research and Higher Education (CINVESTAV) of the National Polytechnic Institute (NPI).
In the study, the population (described or not) is invited to attend MSSI sports centres in Mexico City, where tests will be conducted with children from 8 a.m. every Saturday.
He stressed that the protocol had begun to run at a sports centre in Cuautemok, in the west of Mexico City, and that, since 8 October, the events had been held at a sports centre in Nesaualcovotl, in the east of Mexico City.
Once the target of between 500 and 600 children has been achieved, the study will continue at the Independence Sports Centre (south Mexico City) and finally at the Morelos Sports Centre (north Mexico City).
He explained that the aim of the study was to understand the components and importance of genetics for the development of obesity and to identify the risk factor among children and young Mexicans in order to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On 14 November, World Diabetes Day will be observed, and the main objective is to bring together 3,000 children and adolescents between the ages of 6 and 14, with the permission and supervision of their parents, to complete individual nutrition questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and the history of family hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that lead to diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturday, anthropometry of all participants (weight, growth and waist cover), blood pressure and levels of glucose, fats, cholesterol and insulin, and genetic analysis (to detect genes associated with child obesity) would be carried out.
Cruz Lopez said that the study reflected the concern of health professionals about the alarming increase in the weight of children.
Medical studies carried out between 1999 and 2006 indicate that in just six years there was an increase: 77 per cent of boys were obese, 47 per cent of girls; overweight, there was also a significant increase,” said MSSI.
He said that the validity of the search for markers was based on the fact that the population was different from other peoples in their genetic history.
He reported that, on average, the Mexican is 65 percent of the American Indians, 30 percent of the Europeans, and 5 percent of the Africans, and this condition has affected the genes associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that the main effect of obesity genetics is the inability of the body to burn the excess energy that we consume (calories) and it is delayed in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to the participants was a comprehensive assessment of children, which could determine whether they had any excess weight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark clippings on the neck(s) and forearms means the possibility of a break in metabolism and even a prediabeth.
The information is kept confidential, and the doctors hand it over in writing to the parents, to whom they explain all the dimensions and changes in the way of life that must be made in order to avoid the disease.
Cruz Lopez explained that there are three main causes that cause overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sit-down, or a lack of daily physical activity, the use of most of the day in front of the TV, and the use of small distances of transport instead of walking.
It is also due to high calories, i.e. the increase in the use of sweet drinks and carbohydrates (tomatoes, bread, pizzas, hamburgers, etc.) with high levels of fat and protein and genetic predisposition, as analysed in this programme.
Asphalt UNAM can avoid cracks
Raphael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Department of Chemistry, developed a polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mix of best quality resistant to the environment and temperature.
If the signals sent by the road cover had been given attention, it would have been necessary to repair about 200,000 pits for each rainy season in the Metropolitan Valley, says Rafael Herrera Nahera, a researcher at the UNAM chemical school, and adds that if the process of constructing and maintaining the asphalted road cover is correct, the number of pits can be reduced or reduced to zero.
In his lecture, the International Year of Chemistry ' s Technology View of Pipes states that the laboratory for which it is responsible is developing polymer-modified bitumen to produce a mix of properties close to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nahera said that this type of modified bitumen can be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and thus to resist the formation of pits.
He explained that bitumen, the hardest part of the oil, is the sequence of hydrocarbon molecules, some are the high molecular mass, called asphalt, and others are the low molecular mass, called Maltens, which together provide road cover for its characteristic viscosity.
The viscosity of the bitumen is the fact that in high-temperatures about 180 degrees it behaves like a liquid, at 120 of its viscosity is very high, and at 50 degrees Celsius it stays almost solid, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the resistance of the street asphalt is not permanent, but changes during the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, by a chemical engineer.
The chemist observed that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered with a flexible coating, which is made up of six layers of material, the last three of which include bitumen.
Among the top layers is a bitumen made of small rocks, put into bitumen and then compressed.
Every stone that forms this coating, he said, is immersed in bitumen.
When vehicles are moving and the effort is applied, it helps the forces to distribute very well on the road surface.
If it was a modified asphalt, they'd be even better distributed, said the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt cover, he added, the last layer, which is called a decimation layer, is made of a small stone, in fact sand also immersed in asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will be in contact with the wheels of the transport, it must have more resistance than asphalt coatings and provide for road friction.
As part of the road surface that will receive and distribute this effort, the wear layer also requires the proper thickness, and the material from which it is made must be taken into account.
The weather, especially the humidity and temperature swings, are also very important factors for consideration, especially water, he said, because it has a significant impact on asphalt.
When the ground is raw, the water penetrates the coating, and it's hard to get out of it, it's softening all the layers of the coating, and so the formation of the pit.
In the formation of the pit, he said, the first thing to wear out is the wear layer, and then it only affects the bitumen, but the damage doesn't happen instantly, which is a process that should be taken into account at the first signs of maintenance programmes.
A member of the National Research System also explained that transport is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each coating must always be linked to the transport load and must be guaranteed to meet this requirement in order to prevent the frequent occurrence of pits.
Rafael Herrera said that a lot of bitumen still needs to be studied and done, for example, with bitumen emulsions, which in other countries are already in the market and even help to fix holes with ease and with no high temperatures.
