This was the work of the man who identified the body of Alfonso Cano.
CSI from Cali has entered history as a man who confirmed the death of Alfonso Cano.
The work of these employees is key.
On November 4, CTI Cali entered history as a man who confirmed the identity of the head of the FARC, Alfonso Kano, by comparing his fingerprints.
Of the seven CTI experts, Elizar Gonzalez, a man from Puerto Tehad, who had spent 21 years in the field of judicial investigation, had been in the queue this week.
At the beginning of his career, Gonzalez worked in the cities of Chocó, where he often had to travel for more than five days through the jungle to reach the location of the bodies that had to be identified.
In 2000, he moved to Valle and, after completing the course, became a specialist in the field of forensics, where he studied skin friction, i.e. hands and towers.
During the week of Elizar's operation to identify a man known as Alfonso Kano, he was told to take his clothes for no more than three days.
Something great was coming.
On Friday night, he arrived by helicopter from Cauca to Palmira.
He knew he had to identify two bodies, and one of them was supposed to belong to the man who led the world's oldest guerrilla war, so they asked him to take ten prints of Guillermo Leon Saens (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the research team at the place where the body was located, he did not recognize it externally; it was very different from what was shown in the media.
He had no beard, dressed like a local farmer, no glasses, and a lot thinner.
But the prints don't lie.
Using a magnifying glass, ink, a spatula, and a flashlight, Elizar compared the body's fingerprints to those on the picture.
His eyes did not fail: it was Alfonso Cano.
The same night, the Puerto Tehad representative was asked to confirm to the Minister of Defence, Juan Carlos Pinson, that it was the head of the FARC
Search for Fingerprints
For a Dactilescope specialist at the Sijin unit in Cali, the confession received from President Juan Manuel Santos Elizar Gonzalez at a press conference on the operation against Cano is particularly significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopie is a solid science, and it can play a key role in solving crimes.
In addition to the identification of the bodies, the Dactyloscopics are involved in the investigation of crimes, such as theft and murder, and identify the detainees.
At the time of arrest, many criminals had false or no identity cards.
We take their prints and we're looking for them in the database.
The researcher said that in the event of the theft, he had to take a piece of the wall home because the thief had his hands in this place to possess a safe full of jewels and money.
"It's hard to work with walls because they're not easy to take prints, but in this case we can take a picture of the whole hand and I.D. the criminal who was involved in several thefts," he claims.
Fingerprints also help to exclude or establish the involvement of suspects in murder-related cases.
A dead man with liquor bottles around him was recently found.
In the course of the investigation, it was found that a relative might have been suspected of having committed the crime and that, in fact, the fingerprints on the bottle coincided.
Although it doesn't guarantee that he was a killer, it proves he was at the scene of the murder.
A Dactilescope expert from CTI explained that a chemical or physical reagent is applied to the print sites.
When they appear, a spade or ribbon is used to remove them.
The prints are then sent to Asif, the criminal database, or entered in the register.
"The problem is we still have a lot of undocumented Colombians," said CTI expert.
He explained that not everything was as shown in the CSI TV program.
Just like not all the gold that shines, not everything you touch leaves prints on it.
However, if possible, a comparison is made.
