As we are reminded by economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron in a recent book that summed up the latest data on immigration (Specific People: How Migration Made Our World and Determines Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University, 352 s.), there is a wide consensus among professionals about the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries that accept immigrants.
Restriction of immigration leads to weakening growth and lowering employment.
Fears of immigrant influence are based on the notion that they can replace local workers, especially low-skilled workers, by causing lower wages.
