On Sunday, the Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs of Algeria, Abdelkader Messahel, even stated that the Algerians were now confident.
“The help that the two organizations use, and the reports of the secret services show that they are actively cooperating,” he explained, without entering into detail.
Paris seems to have come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the abduction of two French men in the Niger in January revealed two links.
Kidnapped at a restaurant in Niamey by people close to Aqmi, Antoine de Léokur and Vincent Delori, apparently were killed the next day, along with several of the kidnappers, during an operation conducted by the French Special Forces.
Among the debris left after the operation, the French and Nigerian investigators found a number of SIM cards belonging to the terrorists.
The axis of terror
An analysis of the calls revealed a number of interlocutors in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), the investigators are particularly interested in two numbers, one referring to a Nigerian who lived for a long time in Maidiguri, a city in northern Nigeria, Boko Haram cradle, and the other to a man who is said to be close to Aqmi and a sect.
"This is a step forward, but no doubt we have to wait for more reliable evidence before we talk about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible."
"For many years it has been known that the cult has received external financial and intellectual support and that it is becoming more and more active, "says Kunle Amuvo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, this support has become increasingly evident in Boko Haram's actions and statements and in its methods, which now include the use of suicide bombers and increasingly complex explosive devices of the same type that Aqmi uses.
The international community, led by Washington, now puts pressure on Abuja to draw attention to the problems posed by Boko Haram.
The fact is that the Nigerian authorities have traditionally viewed this group as a community of enlightened people of no interest.
Quick Success
Founded in 2002 in Maidiguri at the mosque, school and imam-fundamentalist Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram - which means "Western education is sin" - preaches the establishment of the Islamic Emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the organization has made rapid progress.
It is politicized and requires strict respect for the sharia, and its activists have begun to fight against the wicked central government.
It focuses on churches, bars, and authorities.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were particularly active in numerous attacks on police stations.
Abuji's reaction is, as usual, uncompromising.
The army blocked the city and left behind 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, taken alive, was killed in prison.
Now the sect is radicalizing and will go beyond its northern suburbs.
Last Christmas, she claimed responsibility for an act that killed 80 people in Joss, and then for another one in Abuja.
In June, in Abuja, Boko Haram launched the first suicide attack against a reinforced police headquarters.
In August, the local representation of the United Nations will be their first international goal.
The establishment of the terrorist axis in Africa, which is coming from Mauritania through Nigeria to Somalia, is now a matter of concern to all security experts.
Now that Aqmi has been strengthened in Mali and Niger, and Somalis from Al-Shabaab are operating in Kenya, Boko Haram is a new threat to the continent.
Last week, during a conversation with the presidents of Goodluck, Jonathan Alain Juppe warned Boko Haram of the danger and expressed his willingness to share all the available information.
