The North Flux, the new gateway to the Russian gas entering Europe.
The Northern Pipeline, which connects Western Europe and Russia directly to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, is being launched.
It is designed to provide gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian giant gas producer, wanted to celebrate the event with pop.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of State and Government, took part last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between the band's performance and the exquisite snacks, in the opening of the North Flux, a new gas pipeline that directly links Russia and Germany underwater.
German chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian president Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fion, and his Dutch colleague Martha Rütte together turned the symbolic valve that controlled the flow of Russian gas into the Western European network.
Under the new gas pipeline, 27.5 million extra cubic meters of gas will flow to Western Europe each year through the first pipeline, which is 1,224 km long, linking Leningrad region to the land of Meklenburg-Mexia.
The second pipeline is to be ready at the end of 2012, providing a total of 55,000 million cubic meters of gas equivalent to the total consumption of France.
And the possibility of constructing a third pipeline in the same direction is already under discussion.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met the ferocious resistance of Poland and the Baltic States.
The Northern Flux will indeed allow the direct flow of gas to Germany, avoiding passage through a third country (Polish or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose some of their power, making it harder for them to influence Russia, threatening to shut down access to Western European markets.
At the most stressful moment of Warsaw's debate, it did not stop from comparing the North Stream with the new “German-Soviet Pact”, insinuating an alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That means the issue is politically sensitive.
By supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is seeking greater security of its supply.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project created a gap between Eastern and Western Europe.
In less than five years, Russia has been able to reach an understanding of a direct union between Russia and the rich Western countries, which consumes large amounts of gas and whose own reserves are running out.
“This gas pipeline is part of the cooperation with Russia, it's a new artery that organically binds us,” said François Fion, opening the gas pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which large gas contracts are both politically and economically important.
All of this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the heads of Gazprom, who were present in large numbers in Lubmin, the point of gas arrival.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater pipe is made of steel in concrete to protect it from the anchors of ships.
It's at the bottom of the sea, at an average depth of 200 meters.
To build it, it was necessary to bypass the minefields left since the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," said Jens Müller, the North Flux Press Secretary.
There was also a need to take many steps to protect fauna and flora.
Pipeline is a long metallic snake weight equal to the weight of 242 Eiffel towers, without ruptures all over the length, without valves, and without service stations.
The control platform was planned in the area of Sweden, but the project managers gave it up because Sweden was not thrilled that a Russian public company would live on its shores forever.
"In the event of an accident, we'll cut the gas flow in less than a minute," Jens Müller claims.
So, in case of a leak, the gas contained in the gas pipeline will be released into the air.
But that seems unlikely to be the designer who designed seams that are designed to leak once every 100,000 years.
The state of the pipeline will be monitored by a submersible robot, which is dragging the ship, for external surveillance, and by a machine circulating inside the pipeline.
A cigar-like machine is injected in a 1 metre diameter pipe and pushed forward by a gas stream.
Upon arrival after 3 full days of travel at 3 meters per second, it provides accurate information about any deformation of the metal.
The gas pipeline was designed for 50 years without the need for the slightest repairs.
Gas circulation is done only by its pressure.
It is 200 bars at the time of departure and 100 bars at the time of arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to implement the project.
The leader is Gazprom, who owns 51% of the capital.
The rest are the German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5 per cent each), the Netherlands Gasunie and the French Group GDF Suez (9 per cent each).
The five companies had established a joint venture, called the North Flux, which had been charged with constructing and operating a gas pipeline.
Its headquarters are in Tsugu in Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the company for 20 years, with the possibility of an extension of the full volume of gas transport.
"Gasprom will pay for the full volume, no matter how much gas will actually be transported," Jens Müller claims.
Financing for the construction of the gas pipeline was provided by 30 per cent of the shareholders and 70 per cent of the bank loans.
The total cost of the work will be Euro7.4 million for two pipelines.
The GDF Suez investment will be about 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are confident that they will pay for their costs, because Gazprom takes all the risks.
The gas line is coming out of the Baltic Sea in Ljubmin to a sandy shore planted with soft trees.
The vents are four and a half meters high and form the outlet of the gas terminal.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas before pumping it into the German gas pipelines.
From last Tuesday, the terminal gets one million cubic meters of gas every hour.
At full capacity, it's going to be 3 million an hour, and in 2012 it's going to be 6 million.
Moleskine Brand Notebook
Moleskine, created by the Italian company 15 years ago, will bring back the taste of the letter.
He's got the aroma of adventure, hours spent after the letter in the light of the candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easy to recognize by the rectangular black cover, by the rubber, by the yellow-and-white pages, as if yellowed over time.
However, the notebook Moleskine, as we know it today, was born in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided to launch design notebooks.
Maria Sebregondi, the company's then consultant, assumed responsibility for launching a new product.
The notebook is inspired by the old technique, the moleskin, the lacquered cotton tissue used, for example, to cover the bench.
This type of notebook is said to be highly appreciated by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine aligned with the taste of today's old and forgotten thing that was cultivating for the Avonardist artists until the 20th century," said Maria Sebregondi, who had since become the managing brand at Modo Modo.
Success has come.
From 2006 to 2010, sales rose by 25 per cent to 12.7 million.
We went far from producing the first years, when only 3,000 notebooks were produced.
Moleskine has crossed Italy's borders and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is hard to set the profile of a typical buyer, because the notebook attracts a businessman, a student, and a man of a free trade.
Moleskine buyers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and educated.
The small Italian company, which initially had only 12 employees, now has 100 and two offices, one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks at Fnac bookshops, shops in small-town centers, and has been able to gain wide visibility.
"We followed the spirit of time and this new need for a letter, despite the advent of e-mail," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural feature is accompanied by the development of Moleskine; the brand has recently organized an exhibition entitled "The Great Way", where architects and artists have shown their own notebooks.
In August, he also launched the cover of a leopard picture at the Locarno Film Festival.
Using his success and his cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified his products, which now include bags, pens, computer bags, and Brand has all kinds of support.
A success that led to envy: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the SG Capital Europe Investment Fund, now Syntegra Capital, which added a new page to Moleskine's history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers so high?
About 19 per cent of disabled people are looking for work.
The 15th week of work for disabled people begins today.
Despite the public charity policy launched in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still double the average, 19 per cent as opposed to 9 per cent for the general population.
Disappointing?
"No," says Eric Blanche, Director General Adapt, an organization that organizes a week of work for disabled people.
"In 15 years, significant progress has been made."
"The unemployment rate was not 2 at that time, but 3 times that."
"But there's still a lot of work to do."
It must be said that there are still many barriers to employment for a disabled person.
Of these, 37 per cent are older than 50 years of age (17 per cent, on average).
They are more of a low-level student: 80 per cent do not have a bachelor ' s degree, and out of 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very common, which is 85 per cent for persons with disabilities, as opposed to 38 per cent on average.
In short, all of these criteria, which make it very difficult to return to work and which are the core of the problem,” says Christian Grapen, Director General Trempling, an association set up in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Here are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about mentality, which is changing, but too slow.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre Association, commissioned by Cité, showed that the managers interviewed had a low level of knowledge of disability and “represented complete people in carts or mentally or mentally disabled”.
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from having 6 per cent of disabled workers, as set out in the Act of 1987.
The last known figures for 2008 are 2.6 per cent.
"Today we're about 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Director General Agefiph, an organization responsible for tax collection from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of “obligated” organizations, like the amounts paid, fell from 59,000 to 46,000 in 2007-2011 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 Act, which raised the tax, created strong pressure on the companies," Pierre Blanc explains.
“But this improvement also reflects a rise in awareness, particularly in large enterprises.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59 per cent of organizations with 20 to 49 employees have disabled workers, compared to 82 per cent of organizations with 100 to 199.
